Memorandum of Understanding: The Regional Clean Energy Advancement Plan
clauses: {'1. Project Scope & Capacity': "A minimum of 750 MW of new renewable energy capacity will be integrated into the regional grid. This will be anchored by Sunstream Renewables' 500 MW shovel-ready 'Golden Mesa Solar Project,' with the remaining 250 MW to be sourced via a competitive bidding process open to diverse technologies (e.g., geothermal, wind) to ensure grid resilience.", '2. Project Timeline': 'The project will be fast-tracked for completion and commercial operation within a firm, non-negotiable 24-month timeline from the signing of this MOU.', '3. Infrastructure Route': 'The primary transmission line will utilize the mutually agreed-upon alternative route, which is approximately 8 miles longer than the initial proposal, to ensure the complete and total avoidance of the environmentally critical Coyote Creek Wetlands.', '4. Funding & Commercial Terms': "A 'Community Benefit Fund' shall be established, funded by a mandatory allocation of 1% of the total final project budget, to be disbursed to low-income and construction-affected communities. To foster a competitive market, a standardized, non-discriminatory transmission 'wheeling' fee will be established for all new generators, capped at a maximum of $5.00 per MWh.", '5. Operational Control & Governance': "Operational control will be managed through a joint partnership. A 'Joint Technical Review' committee, co-chaired by senior technical leads from Legacy Power Corp. and Veridian Co-op, will be immediately established. This committee will oversee the safe and parallel integration of all new physical infrastructure and grid management systems, including Veridian's 'FlowState' software, ensuring the 24-month timeline is met without compromising grid stability or security."}
signatures: ['Maria Flores (Lead Strategist, Green Future Alliance)']
